{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"All direct and transitive dependencies are extracted from the manifest and included in the vulnerability check.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure unit test of the parser can miss failures in module wiring between manifest parsing, lockfile traversal, and dependency graph flattening. The failure boundary is local multi-module integration (possibly filesystem-backed fixtures), not external network/OS APIs.","test_description":"Run the dependency-extraction pipeline against fixture projects (e.g., npm with package-lock, pip with requirements+lock) and assert the emitted dependency set includes both direct and transitive packages before vulnerability lookup input is formed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The vulnerability database query returns results that match the exact version ranges in the manifest, not just the package name.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Mocked API clients can hide real contract mismatches (query params, version-range syntax, server-side matching semantics). To catch true failures, this must exercise the real vulnerability API boundary.","test_description":"Against a real/staging vulnerability DB endpoint, query a package with known CVEs across adjacent versions and assert only CVEs applicable to the manifest’s exact version/range are returned (and non-matching versions are excluded).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The severity sorting places Critical above High above Medium above Low, with CVEs of the same severity sorted by CVSS score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic ordering logic over in-memory data. No I/O or external contract is required to expose real failures here.","test_description":"Call the sorting function with mixed severities and tied severities with different CVSS values; assert strict order: Critical > High > Medium > Low, and descending CVSS within each severity bucket.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The manifest modification changes only the affected dependency's version, leaving all other entries unchanged.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A unit test on a single edit helper may miss parse/serialize side effects (key reordering, formatting drift, incidental edits). A file-level integration test catches real mutation behavior.","test_description":"Apply the updater to a real manifest fixture file and assert diff scope is exactly one dependency version field; verify all other dependency entries and unrelated manifest sections remain byte-for-byte (or structurally) unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real Git hosting APIs and git/diff behavior. In-process mocks can pass while auth, branch, patch application, or PR creation fails in production.","test_description":"In a dedicated test repository, run the PR creation flow end-to-end (branch creation, commit, push, PR open) and assert the PR exists and changed files show only the intended single dependency bump.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A major version bump is correctly identified as a breaking change based on semver comparison.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Semver major-bump detection is deterministic local logic and is best validated directly at function/object boundary.","test_description":"Test semver comparison with a matrix of version transitions (patch, minor, major, pre-release/build metadata) and assert only major increments are flagged as breaking.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When a breaking change is detected, PR creation is skipped and a review flag is surfaced in the scanner output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration across detection, decision gate, PR module, and report generation. A unit test of any one piece can miss wiring bugs; external systems are not required for the minimum failure boundary.","test_description":"Run the scanner orchestration with input that forces a major bump, using a local/in-memory PR adapter, and assert no PR action is executed while output contains an explicit breaking-change review flag.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
